headline: AI Weekly: Mega deals and Molière-inspired plays
summary: STORY: From multi-billion dollar deals, to plays written with AI -- this is AI Weekly. -- :: AI WeeklyMicrosoft and Nvidia have made a mega deal with Claude-maker Anthropic, featuring tens of billions of dollars of spending.It includes a $30 billion commitment by the AI company to Microsoft's cloud services, Azure. And both Nvidia and Microsoft committing up to $10 billion and $5 billion in Anthropic, respectively. The agreement brings together major players in the AI industry, with Claude being a major rival to ChatGPT.Elon Musk’s artificial-intelligence startup xAI is in advanced talks to raise $15 billion in new equity - at a valuation of $230 billion.That's according to the Wall Street Journal. The new valuation would more than double the amount disclosed in March.The startup has been rapidly scaling its data-center footprint to train more advanced models, as it tries to close the gap with OpenAI’s ChatGPT and Anthropic’s Claude. Bank of America is planning to spend $4 billion more in new technology, including AI, to boost bankers' productivity and drive revenue growth.The bank's chief technology officer said its 18,000 developers have used AI agents for the past year, with significant gains in productivity.The second-biggest U.S. lender sends AI-generated market information to its financial advisers, combined with data on clients' portfolios, so that bankers can better tailor their investment advice.Nvidia's move to use smartphone-style memory chips in its AI servers could cause server-memory prices to double by late 2026.That's according to a report published Wednesday by Counterpoint Research.Electronics supply chains worldwide have been hit by a shortage of legacy memory chips in the last two months.Manufacturers have turned their focus to high-end memory chips suited to semiconductors.Counterpoint says Nvidia's decision to reduce AI server power costs, by changing the kind of memory chip it uses, could create sudden demand that the industry is not prepared for.:: Sorbonne Universite / Theatre Moliere SorbonneAnd, scholars have teamed up with an AI collective in Paris to create a new play written in the style of the famous 17th-century playwright Moliere.Over the last three years, the team has trained the French-developed Mistral AI on Moliere's works, personal library texts, and historical documents to replicate his language and humor.A production called "The Astrologer or the False Omens" is set to debut at the Chateau de Versailles in May 2026.

headline: Elon Musk, Jensen Huang to talk AI at US-Saudi investment forum
summary: WASHINGTON (Reuters) -Tesla CEO Elon Musk and Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang will take part in a discussion on ​advances in artificial intelligence and technology at a U.S.-Saudi ‌Arabia investment forum in Washington on Wednesday, according to a document seen by Reuters.  "This conversation ‌will explore the emerging forces shaping the next wave of technological progress, highlighting the architectures, models, and investments powering a more intelligent and interconnected future," the document said.  The event is planned for the day after Saudi Crown Prince ⁠Mohammed bin Salman, widely ‌known by his initials MBS, met with President Donald Trump at the White House.

headline: Nvidia Results and Delayed Jobs Data Set Up Critical Test for Wall Street
summary: After mounting scrutiny of stratospheric tech investments, as well as a blackout of federal data during the longest government shutdown in U.S. history, Wall Street awaits two reports that stand to reshape its outlook for the months ahead.  AI poster-child  Nvidia  is due to report earnings after the closing bell Wednesday, offering a snapshot of demand for chips that are a linchpin in the tech mania that has lifted markets and helped buoy the economy.  The two releases will provide critical signals for investors after the most significant pullback in markets since President Trump’s tariff proposals sent stocks and bonds haywire in April.

headline: Review & Preview: Risky Business
summary: The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 499 points, or 1.1%, while the Nasdaq Composite closed down 1.2%.  “Stocks are suffering losses for the fourth consecutive day as Wall Street adopts a risk-off posture, considering valuation worries, household spending anxiety, employment angst, and elevated inflation that is keeping the Fed at bay and increasingly preventing it from intervening,” writes José Torres, senior economist at Interactive Brokers.  Torres notes that investors spent the day bailing out of the market ahead of tomorrow’s earnings report from Nvidia, as the AI skepticism theme gains traction.

headline: Gold Steadies as Investors Weigh Stock Jitters, Rate-Cut Outlook
summary: A high-stakes earnings report from Nvidia Corp. due Wednesday will test investors’ nerves over stocks linked to artificial-intelligence developments.  While gold often performs well when investors seek refuge from market turmoil, it can also suffer in the short term as traders are forced to unwind leveraged positions.  Comments by several Federal Reserve policymakers have also lowered expectations of a US rate cut, which would normally be a tailwind for non-yielding bullion.
